Chief Constable '''Henry Solomon''' (1794 - 14 March 1844)<ref>{{cite book|last=Erredge|first=John Ackerson |title=History of Brighthelmston, or Brighton as I view it and others knew it |publisher=Lewis|location=Brighton|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=uK8HAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA246&dq=%22Henry+Solomon%22+Brighton&as_brr=3|accessdate=2008-04-24|page=246}}</ref> was a [[police officer]] who became the first [[Chief Constable]] of [[Sussex Police|Brighton Borough Police]] in [[East Sussex]], England.<ref name=MSS>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhhc-shul.org/publicity/msbiographicaltour.pdf|title=Henry Solomon|work=Middle Street Synagogue, a part of Brighton's history|publisher=Friends of Middle Street Historic Synagogue|page=19|accessdate=2008-04-24}}</ref>

Solomon was appointed as Chief Constable <U+2014> the highest rank in the force <U+2014> on 18 May 1838,<ref name=argus>{{cite news|url=http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2004/4/2/115942.html|title=New buses celebrate city's past|date=2004-04-02|work=The Argus|publisher=Newsquest Media Group|accessdate=2008-04-24}}</ref> which was a notable appointment in that period as he was a [[Jews|Jewish]] man.<ref name=SusPol>{{cite web|url=http://www.sussex.police.uk/about_us/aboutus_museum.asp|title=Old Police Cells Museum|publisher=Sussex Police|accessdate=2008-04-24}}</ref> He became the superior officer to two [[Superintendent (police)|superintendent]]s, three [[Inspector#United Kingdom|inspector]]s, twenty-four [[constable]]s and a night constable <U+2014> a total of thirty-one officers for a population of around 47,000.<ref>http://www.the-spi.co.uk/CASE%20FILES/OLD%20POLICE%20MUSEUM/History.html</ref>

While interviewing a prisoner <U+2014> 23-year-old John Lawrence, for theft of a roll of carpet <U+2014> on 13 March 1844, Solomon was bludgeoned by Lawrence with a [[Fire iron|poker]], causing a head injury from which he later died.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Annual Register or a View of the History and Politics of the Year 1844|editor=Edmund Burke|publisher=Woodfall & Son|location=London|year=1845|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jc0kh800jGIC&pg=RA3-PA29&dq=%22Henry+Solomon%22+Brighton&as_brr=3|accessdate=2008-04-24|page=29}}</ref> An appeal to which [[Queen Victoria]] gave <U+00A3>50 raised a large sum for the welfare of his widow and nine children.<ref name=MSS /> Lawrence was found guilty of [[Murder in English law|murder]] at [[Lewes]] [[Assizes]] and publicly [[hanging|hanged]] at [[Horsham]].

Solomon is thought to be the only Chief Constable in the United Kingdom to have been murdered in his own police station.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/southern_counties/6183136.stm|title=Lottery boost for police museum |date=2006-11-25|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2008-04-24}}</ref><ref name=CTN>{{cite web|url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/notorious_murders/classics/haunted_crime_scene2/11.html|title=Tied to His Work |work=Notorious murders/Timeless classics|publisher=Courtroom Television Network, LLC., Time Warner |accessdate=2008-04-24}}</ref> His ghost reputedly haunts the basement of the building, now a [[town hall]].<ref name=SusPol /><ref name=CTN /> He is buried in the Florence Place Old Jewish Burial Ground in Brighton's [[Round Hill, Brighton|Round Hill]] district,<ref name="Sharman Kadish 2006, p. 79">Sharman Kadish, Jewish Heritage in England : An Architectural Guide, English Heritage, 2006, p. 79</ref> where he has been considered to be the 'celebrity' grave.<ref>{{cite book|last=Singh|first=Tejvir |title=New Horizons in Tourism: Strange Experiences and Stranger Practices|publisher=CABI Publishing|location=Cambridge, MA |year=2004|isbn=0-85199-863-1|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_8ek9zCDPCYC&pg=RA1-PA76&dq=%22Henry+Solomon%22+Brighton&as_brr=3&sig=G_LHy8gAiiWzHXt_TFk3AC5OHHU#PRA1-PA76,M1|accessdate=2008-04-24|page=76}}</ref> In 2004, his was one of several local names to be chosen to appear on the front of a new fleet of buses in Brighton.<ref name=argus />

The inscription on Solomon's gravestone reads: 15 years chief officer of police / of the town of Brighton / who was brutally murdered / while in the public discharge / of the duties of his office / on the 14th day of March 1844 / in the fiftieth year of his age.<ref name="Sharman Kadish 2006, p. 79"/>

